oc:kn_0a91afde a oc:DesignPrinciple,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When designing concurrent Erlang systems" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Create processes liberally — each BEAM process is lightweight with its own heap and mailbox. Favor 'process per entity' designs to maximize isolation and scalability." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Process creation on the BEAM is extremely cheap (~1-3μs), enabling fine-grained concurrency without OS thread overhead." ;
    oc:severityLevel "HIGH" .

oc:kn_220e5ed7 a oc:KnowledgeNode,
        oc:Standard ;
    oc:appliesToContext "All inter-process communication in Erlang" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Use message passing exclusively for inter-process communication. Never share state between processes." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Shared memory introduces race conditions and locks; message passing preserves isolation guarantees and eliminates concurrency bugs." ;
    oc:severityLevel "CRITICAL" .

oc:kn_4ebf59b6 a oc:Heuristic,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When choosing between links and monitors for failure detection" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Use monitors for one-way observation of processes; use bidirectional links only when processes should share fate (e.g., supervisor-worker pairs). Trap exits in supervisor processes." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Monitors are composable and don't affect the observed process. Links create bidirectional dependencies that require careful exit trapping to handle correctly." ;
    oc:severityLevel "MEDIUM" .

oc:kn_93b8e673 a oc:KnowledgeNode,
        oc:PerformanceProfile ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When optimizing concurrent Erlang applications" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Profile concurrent systems to identify bottlenecks and optimize hot paths. Keep process state minimal to reduce per-process memory usage." ;
    oc:hasRationale "BEAM can schedule millions of processes, but mailbox size and message passing frequency dominate performance characteristics." ;
    oc:severityLevel "MEDIUM" .

oc:kn_c6631687 a oc:AntiPattern,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When designing process coordination" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Avoid using shared ETS tables as mutex replacements and overusing registered process names — these create contention points and defeat isolation." ;
    oc:hasRationale "ETS as mutex introduces lock contention. Registered names are global singletons that limit scalability and create single points of failure." ;
    oc:severityLevel "MEDIUM" .

oc:kn_d5929fc6 a oc:AntiPattern,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When writing receive blocks" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Never accumulate unhandled messages in mailboxes — every message type must be matched in a receive clause. Use timeouts to prevent indefinite blocking." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Unmatched messages accumulate in mailboxes causing memory leaks and performance degradation. Missing timeouts cause processes to hang indefinitely." ;
    oc:severityLevel "HIGH" .

oc:kn_fe80d4bb a oc:Constraint,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When deciding whether to spawn processes for parallel work" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Use processes for coarse-grained concurrency tasks. Avoid spawning processes for fine-grained parallelism where the overhead exceeds the benefit." ;
    oc:hasRationale "While BEAM processes are cheap, each still has overhead (heap allocation, scheduling). Very fine-grained tasks are better handled sequentially or with NIFs." ;
    oc:severityLevel "LOW" .

